{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn1.46:1.1": "The nymphs (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>accharā</i>, “aquatics”, perhaps originally cloud-deities) were known from Vedic times as beautiful dancers and musicians often romantically entwined with the <i lang='pi' translate='no'>gandhabba</i>. ",
    "sn1.46:1.2": "As horrifying as nymphs are seductive, the flesh-eating <i lang='pi' translate='no'>pisāca</i> (Sanskrit <i lang='pi' translate='no'>piśāca</i>) arises in troops under cover of night and slips through the air wreaking havoc. ",
    "sn1.46:1.3": "Delusion contains both desire and aversion. ",
    "sn1.46:2.1": "This Sutta contrasts the “direct” way with the “deluding” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>mohana</i>) way. This recalls the notion that the teaching shows the way to those who are lost (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>mūḷhassa vā maggaṁ ācikkheyya</i>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn7.1/en/sujato#9.3'>SN 7.1:9.3</a>). This echoes the common description of the Saṅgha as practicing the way that is “direct”, suggesting that they are proceeding directly along a known route (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn11.3/en/sujato#11.2'>SN 11.3:11.2</a>). ",
    "sn1.46:2.4": "Normally <i lang='pi' translate='no'>dhammacakka</i>, the “wheel of the teaching”, is singular, this being a unique plural. The commentary explains as mental and physical energy. "
  },
